        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>JACOB VOORSANGER&#44;<lb/>
                HOUSTON&#44;<lb/>
                TEXAS.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dec. 11 1879<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev &#38; Dr Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Though engaged in finishing my<lb/> Sermon for this evening I cannot bear to leave<lb/> your kind answer to my first unanswered any<lb/> longer.  I was right when I expressed my confidence<lb/> that spite of my long neglect you would write<lb/> to me as if you had seen me but yesterday.  Thank<lb/> you with all my heart.<lb/></p>
            <p>Your words of advice have comforted me very<lb/> much&#44; I am in so far unlike a good many of<lb/> my age &#38; ability&#44; that&#44; whilst possessing a goodly<lb/> portion of confidence in myself I am not suf<lb/>ficiently vain or conceited to consider myself<lb/> infallible.  At times I doubt my own ability to<lb/> carry on my great work.  But such words as yours<lb/> are like a prop under my arms&#44; and you don&#39;t<lb/> know how I appreciate it.  With respect to the<lb/> doctrine of eternity of matter&#44; I am glad that I may<lb/> entertain its believe without violating the principles of<lb/> our holy religion.  It is a great relief to me&#44; to be able<lb/> to think without doing offense to my religion.  In reading<lb/> the above on the subject I find a disquisition on the<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; the perpetual or eternal force.  Ulendel&#44;<lb/>ssohn&#91;&#63;&#93; who as you are aware wrote a &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to the &#91;&#63;&#93; has much to say on the subject but<lb/> concludes that any mixture of the Platonic &#38; Aristotelian<lb/> theories with Judaism is dangerous to the individual<lb/> thinker.  I am inclined to think he is right.  It avails<lb/> nothing&#8212;the pondering upon abstract matters&#44; though<lb/> it develops the mental faculties.  I envy you&#44; who<lb/> can act &#38; live with simply &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/>  No doubt my time of trial &#38; reflection will come&#44;<lb/> &#38; I shall be thankful that they will restore me my<lb/> former childlike faith.  In fact I feel that I could be doubly<lb/> grateful for affliction if it would tend to restore<lb/> to me <del>my</del> certainty &#38; remove doubt.  Believing as I<lb/> do firmly &#38; unwaveringly in one&#44; &#91;&#63;&#93; God&#44; as the<lb/> &#91;&#63;&#93; of my people &#38; the divine revelation to man<lb/> I am sadly swayed between conflicting opinions<lb/> upon minor matters.  And in such a state it affords<lb/> one great consolation to hear from lips as yours that our<lb/> blessed religion allows <del>affords</del> the very widest scope of private<lb/> interpretation.  Had Moses ever doubted <del>but</del> that those who<lb/> really &#38; earnestly seek God would be sure to find him<lb/> he would have &#34;hedged&#34; even more than the Rabbis did<lb/> Nothing new for the present.  The weather here is glori<lb/>ously in unison with the warm feelings stirred up<lb/> by reading the memorable feats of the Maccabes.<lb/>  May the friendly winter sun bring you as pleasant<lb/> Chanuka thoughts as they have brought to<lb/></p>
            <p>yours&#44; faithfully<lb/>
                	Jacob Voorsanger<lb/></p>
            <p>324 Congress Str.</p>
        </body>
